ms\n|-\n| 2014\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Super 8\"\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n! scope=\"row\"| \"24 Frames\"\n| \n|-\n| 2017\n! scope=\"row\"| \"If We Were Vampires\"\n| Joshua Britt & Neilson Hubbard\n|}\n\n===Producer credit===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:4.0em;\" | Year\n! style=\"width:20em;\" | Album\n! style=\"width:20em;\" | Artist\n! style=\"width:20em;\" | Label\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2012\n| ''Burn. Flicker. Die.''\n| [[American Aquarium]]\n| [[Last Chance Records]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2019\n| ''[[Fever Breaks]]''\n| [[Josh Ritter]]\n| Pytheas Recordings\n|}\n\n==Equipment==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=February 2017}}\n\n===Guitars===\n* [[C. F. Martin & Company|Martin]] Custom Jason Isbell D-18\n* Martin Custom D-35\n* Martin Authentic Series 1939 D-18\n* Martin D-28 12 string\n* Baxendale Custom Acoustic\n* Martin OM-28\n* Martin HD-28 Retro\n* Custom \"Dobrato\" Resonator - Steel Body w/ Bigsby (Castle Creek Guitars, Gunnison, CO)\n* [[Duesenberg Guitars|Duesenberg]] Starplayer TV Goldtop\n* [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] Stratocaster\n* [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] Modified 'Coodercaster'\n* [[First Act]] Custom Delgada w/ Bigsby\n* First Act Custom Delia LS w/ Bigsby\n* First Act Delia LS (standard fixed-bridge version)\n* [[Gibson Guitar Corporation|Gibson]] Les Paul Standard\n* Gibson ES-335 (1961)\n* Gibson Les Paul Standard \"Red Eye\" (1959) Formerly owned by Ed King \n* Gibson collector's choice #12 les paul\n* Gretsch Duo Jet - 1959 (w/ Bigsby, purchased from Dave Cobb)\n* Gretsch White Falcon purchased by Amanda Shires from John Prine\n* [[Reverend Musical Instruments|Reverend]] Buckshot\n* Reverend Flatroc w/ Les Trem\n* [[Harmony Company|Harmony]] Archtop<ref name=HearYa-2011>{{cite web|last=Oz|title=An Interview With Jason Isbell \u2013 Here We Rest.|url=http://www.hearya.com/2011/04/05/an-interview-with-jason-isbell-here-we-rest/|work=Hear Ya|accessdate=27 March 2014|date=5 April 2011}}</ref>\n* Fender Telecaster\n\n===Amps===\n* [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] [[Vibroverb]]\n* [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] Princeton\n*Fender Deluxe Reverb\n* Fender pro (non-reverb)\n* Sommatone Roaring-40 head and 2x12 cabinet\n* [[Magnatone]] Super Fifty-Nine\n* [[Tone King]] Imperial MKII\n* [[Vox (musical equipment)|Vox]] AC30HW\n\n===Other gear===\n* Marion Henry Guitar pedals\n* Mr. B's Bottleneck Guitar slides\n* POG electro-harmonix octave generator<ref name=HearYa-2011/>\n* Klon Centaur\n* [[Z.Vex Effects|Z.Vex]] Box of Rock overdrive pedal<ref name=HearYa-2011/>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n===[[Americana Music Honors & Awards]]===\nThe [[Americana Music Honors & Awards]] celebrate outstanding achievement in the genre of Americana. Isbell has won nine awards out of 16 nominations.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Category !! Nominated Work !! Result\n|-\n| 2009 || Album of the Year || ''[[Jason Isbell and The 400 Unit]]'' || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2012 ||  Song of the Year || \"Alabama Pines\" || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Album of the Year || ''[[Here We Rest]]'' || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Artist of the Year || Jason Isbell || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2014 || Song of the Year || \"Cover Me Up\" || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Album of the Year || [[Southeastern (album)|''Southeastern'']] || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|Artist of the Year || rowspan=2|Jason Isbell || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2015 || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2016 || Album of the Year || ''[[Something More Than Free]]'' || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Song of the Year || \"24 Frames\" || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3|Artist of the Year || rowspan=3|Jason Isbell || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| 2017 || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=4| 2018 || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Album of the Year || ''[[The Nashville Sound]]'' || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Duo/Group of the Year || Jason Isbell & the 400 Unit || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Song of the Year || \"If We Were Vampires\" || {{Won}}\n|}\n\n===[[Country Music Association Awards]]===\nThe [[CMA Awards]] celebrate outstanding achievement in country music. Isbell has received one nomination.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Category !! Nominated Work !! Result\n|-\n| [[51st Annual Country Music Association Awards|2017]] || [[Country Music Association Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] || ''[[The Nashville Sound]]'' || {{Nominated}}\n|}\n\n===[[Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum|Country Music Hall of Fame]]===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Category !! Nominated Work !! Result\n|-\n| 2017 || Artist-in-Residence || N/A || {{won}}\n|}\n\n===[[Daytime Emmy Awards]]===\nThe [[Daytime Emmy Awards]] are American accolades bestowed by the [[New York, New York|New York]]\u2013based [[National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]] in recognition of excellence in [[United States|American]] [[daytime television]] programming. Isbell has received one nomination.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Category !! Nominated Work !! Result\n|-\n| [[45th Daytime Emmy Awards|2018]] || [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Musical Performance in a Daytime Program|Outstanding Musical Performance in a Daytime Program]] || \"Cumberland Gap\"/\"If We Were Vampires\" on [[CBS This Morning]] || {{Nominated}}\n|}\n\n===[[Grammy Awards]]===\nThe [[Grammy Awards]] celebrate outstanding achievement in music. Isbell has won 4 awards out of 4 nominations.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Category !! Nominated Work !! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[58th Annual Grammy Awards|2016]] || [[Grammy Award for Best American Roots Song|Best American Roots Song]] || \"24 Frames\" || {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Americana Album|Best Americana Album]]|| ''[[Something More Than Free]]'' || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[60th Annual Grammy Awards|2018]] || [[Grammy Award for Best American Roots Song|Best American Roots Song]] || \"If We Were Vampires\" || {{won}} \n|-\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Americana Album|Best Americana Album]]|| ''[[The Nashville Sound]]'' || {{won}}\n|}\n\n===[[Americana Music Honors & Awards|UK Americana Awards]]===\nThe [[Americana Music Honors & Awards|UK Americana Awards]] celebrate the best roots music released in the UK and internationally. Isbell has received two nomination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.entertainment-focus.com/music-section/music-news/robert-plant-to-receive-lifetime-achievement-award-at-uk-americana-awards-2018/|title=Robert Plant to receive Lifetime Achievement Award at UK Americana Awards 2018 - Entertainment Focus|website=Entertainment-focus.com}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Category !! Nominated Work !! Result\n|-\n|2018 || International Album of the Year || ''[[The Nashville Sound]]'' || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2016 || International Artist of the Year || ''Jason Isbell'' || {{Won}}\n|}\n\n==Home media==\n* Weissman, Barr, Patterson Hood, Mike Cooley, Shonna Tucker, Brad Morgan, [[John Neff (Musician)|John Neff]], and Jason Isbell. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/709937022 The Secret to a Happy Ending: A Documentary About the Drive-by Truckers.]'' New York: ATO Records, 2011. (DVD of 2009 documentary)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Drive-By Truckers]]\n* [[Muscle Shoals Sound Studio]]\n* [[Muscle Shoals, Alabama]]\n* [[Amanda Shires]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Jason Isbell}}\n* [http://www.jasonisbell.com JasonIsbell.com] (official site)\n\n{{Jason Isbell}}\n{{Drive-By Truckers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Isbell, Jason}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lauderdale County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Singers from Alabama]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American rock singers]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:New West Records artists]]\n[[Category:Americana Music Honors & Awards winners]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Alabama]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Drive-By Truckers members]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Alabama]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Alabama]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                 = Jason Isbell\n| background           = solo_singer\n| image                = Jason Isbell at Bowery Ballroom.JPG\n| alt                  = Isbell with the 400 Unit at Bowery Ballroom, New York City in January 2013\n| caption              = Isbell with the 400 Unit at Bowery Ballroom, NYC in January 2013\n| birth_name           = Michael Jason Isbell<ref name=BMI-RepertoireProfile>{{cite web|url=http://repertoire.bmi.com/Catalog.aspx?detail=writerid&page=1&fromrow=1&torow=25&keyid=887074&subid=0|title=Songwriter/Composer: Isbell Michael Jason |work=[[Broadcast Music, Inc.|BMI]] |accessdate=July 3, 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1979|02|01}}\n| birth_place          = [[Green Hill, Alabama]], U.S.\n| genre                = {{flatlist|\n* [[Country music|Country]]\n* [[alternative country]]\n* [[Southern rock]]\n}}\n| occupation           = Singer-songwriter, guitarist\n| instrument           = Vocals, guitar, electronic keyboard\n| years_active         = 2000\u2013present\n| label                = {{flatlist|\n* Lightning Rod\n* [[New West Records|New West]]\n* Southeastern\n* [[Thirty Tigers]]\n}}\n| associated_acts      = [[Drive-By Truckers]], [[Amanda Shires]],\n| website              = {{URL|jasonisbell.com}}\n}}\n'''Michael Jason Isbell''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u026a|z|b|\u028a|l|}};<ref name=\"WTF-Maron-2014\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wtfpod.com/podcast/episodes/episode_482_-_jason_isbell|title=Episode 482 - Jason Isbell|last=Maron|first=Marc|date=26 March 2014|format=podcast|url-access=subscription |work=[[WTF with Marc Maron]]|accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref> born February 1, 1979) is an American singer-songwriter and guitarist from [[Green Hill, Alabama]], in [[Lauderdale County, Alabama|Lauderdale County]]. He is known for his solo career, his work with the band [[Jason Isbell and The 400 Unit|The 400 Unit]], and as a former member of [[Drive-By Truckers]] for six years, from 2001 to 2007.<ref name=AllMusic-bio>{{cite web|last=Monger|first=James Christopher|title=Jason Isbell - Biography|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/jason-isbell-mn0000562615/biography|work=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=GQ-3CountryBadasses-2016>{{cite news|last1=Welch|first1=Will|title=Meet Three Country Badasses Who Are Shaking Up the Nashville Establishment|url=https://www.gq.com/story/meet-the-country-badasses-from-nashville|accessdate=10 January 2016|work=[[GQ]]|date=7 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=GQ-KingAmericana-2016>{{cite news|last1=Welch|first1=Will|title=The GQ&A: Jason Isbell, the New King of Americana Music|url=https://www.gq.com/story/jason-isbell-king-of-americana-music|accessdate=10 January 2016|work=[[GQ]]|date=7 January 2016}}</ref> Isbell has won four [[Grammy Award]]s.\n\n==Early life==\nIsbell was born in [[Green Hill, Alabama]], two miles from the [[Alabama]]/[[Tennessee]] state line,<ref name=\"SpinItLoud-2009\">{{cite web|url=http://spinitloud.com/?p=61|title=Jason Isbell|year=2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327234639/http://spinitloud.com/?p=61|archive-date=27 March 2014|work=Spin It Loud|accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref> the son of interior designer mother Angela Hill Barnett and house painter Mike Isbell.<ref name=NYT-Mag-2013>{{cite news|last=Garner|first=Dwight|title=Jason Isbell, Unloaded|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/02/magazine/jason-isbell-unloaded.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|accessdate=27 March 2014|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=31 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=CarthelIsbell-obit-2002>{{cite web|title=Carthel E. Isbell|url=http://www.timesdaily.com/archives/article_da82aae8-fbfe-5442-bd58-3b12e009e648.html?mode=jqm|work=Florence Times Daily|date=19 September 2002}}</ref> Isbell's mother was only 17 years old (and his father 19 years old) when he was born<ref name=\"HuffPo-SMTF-2015\">{{cite news|last1=Bialas|first1=Michael|title=During the Long, Hot Summer, Jason Isbell Warms Up to Become One Glad Dad|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/michael-bialas/during-the-long-hot-summe_b_7966884.html|accessdate=11 August 2015|work=[[Huffington Post]]|date=10 August 2015}}</ref> and is the subject of a song, \"Children of Children\".<ref name=\"CBS-SMTF-2015\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/videos/the-fall-and-rise-of-jason-isbell/|title=The fall and rise of Jason Isbell|last=Mason|first=Anthony|date=9 August 2015|work=[[CBS News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150810043151/http://www.cbsnews.com/videos/the-fall-and-rise-of-jason-isbell/|archive-date=10 August 2015|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref> Isbell's parents divorced, and he has two much younger half-siblings, Chantry Barnett and Emily Isbell.<ref name=\"WTF-Maron-2014\" />\n\nIsbell grew up in rural [[North Alabama]]. His grandparents lived on a farm down the road, next to the school that Isbell attended; they looked after him while his parents were at work. His grandfather and uncle taught him to play various musical instruments,<ref name=\"CBS-SMTF-Extra-2015\">{{cite news|last1=Mason|first1=Anthony|title=Jason Isbell on his musical education (web extra)|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/videos/jason-isbell-on-his-musical-education/|accessdate=9 August 2015|work=[[CBS News]]|date=8 August 2015}}</ref> including the [[mandolin]] when he was 6 years old as it was easier for him to grip as a small child. They enjoyed [[gospel music]], [[bluegrass music]], and the [[Grand Ole Opry]]. In high school, he played [[trumpet]] and [[French horn]].<ref name=\"WTF-Maron-2014\" /> Isbell's family would get together and play music every week, sometimes twice a week, which Isbell said has a lot to do with where he comes from and the family's focus on music.<ref name=\"CharlestonCity-2011\">{{cite news|last=Booth|first=Jared|title=Jason Isbell talks writing, war, and family life|url=http://www.charlestoncitypaper.com/charleston/jason-isbell-rests-his-case/Content?oid=3345499|accessdate=29 March 2014|newspaper=[[Charleston City Paper]]|date=May 11, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"IllEnt-2007\">{{cite web|last=Dodds|first=M.S.|title=Jason Isbell interview|url=http://illinoisentertainer.com/2007/06/jason-isbell-interview/|work=Illinois Entertainer|accessdate=27 March 2014|date=28 June 2007}}</ref> Isbell's paternal grandfather, who came from a musical family, was a [[Pentecostalism|Pentecostal]] preacher and played guitar in church. Isbell spent his childhood attending both the Pentecostal church and the stricter Church of Christ, which permitted only singing (no musical instruments).<ref name=\"WTF-Maron-2014\" /><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/jason-isbell-5-things-we-learned-from-new-interview-119150/|title=Jason Isbell: 5 Things We Learned From New Interview|first=Jeff|last=Gage|date=9 June 2017|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=19 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIsbell started playing in a garage band and a country cover band when he was 14 or 15 years old with his friend, songwriter [[Chris Tompkins]].<ref name=\"RStone-Sober-2013\">{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/jason-isbell-theres-still-just-as-much-awe-in-sobriety-20130801|title=Jason Isbell: 'There's Still Just as Much Awe' in Sobriety|last=Sullivan|first=James|date=1 August 2013|newspaper=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430095942/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/jason-isbell-theres-still-just-as-much-awe-in-sobriety-20130801|archive-date=30 April 2016|accessdate=30 March 2014}}</ref> They played at the [[Grand Ole Opry]] when Isbell was 16.<ref name=\"WTF-Maron-2014\" />\n\nIsbell attended the [[University of Memphis]],<ref name=\"ConnectSavannah-2014\">{{cite web|last=DeYoung|first=Bill|title=SMF review: Jason Isbell|url=http://www.connectsavannah.com/savannah/smf-review-jason-isbell/Content?oid=2369820|work=[[Connect Savannah]]|accessdate=30 March 2014|date=19 March 2014}}</ref> studying English and creative writing. He did not graduate, still requiring one physical education credit.<ref name=\"WTF-Maron-2014\" />\n\n==Career==\nWhen Isbell was a teenager, many musicians took him under their wing.<ref name=RollingStone-SXSW-2011 /> He got to know session bassist [[David Hood]], the father of [[Drive-By Truckers]] co-founder [[Patterson Hood]], because Hood was in the [[Florence, Alabama]] area and played around town on Friday and Saturday nights in local restaurants and bars. By this time, Patterson Hood and his future Drive-By Truckers co-founder, [[Mike Cooley (musician)|Mike Cooley]],  were older and had moved out of town. Isbell would go watch David Hood and others perform. It took a while, but once he finally got up the nerve to tell them he played, they'd have him sit in with them, which resulted in friendship and mentorship.<ref name=WTF-Maron-2014 />\n\nIsbell submitted demos and eventually got a publishing deal with [[FAME Studios]] of [[Muscle Shoals, Alabama]], when he was 21 years old. He worked for FAME until he joined the [[Drive-by Truckers]].<ref name=RollingStone-SXSW-2011 />\n\n===Drive-By Truckers===\n[[File:JasonIsbell.JPG|thumbnail|Jason Isbell performing with [[Drive-By Truckers]] in [[Auburn, Alabama|Auburn]], [[Alabama]], in 2005]]\nAfter working as a songwriter, in 2001 at the age of 22, Isbell joined the rock band [[Drive-By Truckers]] while they toured in support of their album ''[[Southern Rock Opera]]''.<ref name=\"LostWriters-2006\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lostwriters.net/archive_popup.php?c=czozOiIyNDkiOw==|title=An Artist Revealed: Interview with Jason Isbell |last=Schmergel |first=Daniel Patrick |date=24 April 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311124053/http://www.lostwriters.net/archive_popup.php?c=czozOiIyNDkiOw%3D%3D |archive-date=11 March 2007 |work=Lost Writers |accessdate=27 March 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The band operates out of [[Athens, Georgia]], where Isbell lived while with the band. [[Patterson Hood]] recalls that he met Isbell through Dick Cooper, a mutual friend from Muscle Shoals.<ref name=\"WTF-Maron-Hood-2014\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wtfpod.com/podcast/episodes/episode_483_-_patterson_hood|title=Episode 483 - Patterson Hood|last=Maron|first=Marc|date=28 March 2014|format=podcast|url-access=subscription |work=[[WTF with Marc Maron|WTF Podcast]]|accessdate=30 March 2014}}</ref> Hood already knew [[Shonna Tucker]] and invited Isbell to join Drive-by Truckers after he sat in with the group at an acoustic house party when guitarist Rob Malone didn't show up.<ref name=\"AmSongwriter-2013\">{{cite web|last=Leahey|first=Andrew|title=Jason Isbell Keeps on Truckin'|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2013/09/jason-isbell-keeps-on-truckin/|work=[[American Songwriter]]|accessdate=30 March 2014|date=17 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nIsbell recorded and contributed many songs to Drive-by Truckers for their next three albums, 2003's ''[[Decoration Day (album)|Decoration Day]],'' 2004's ''[[The Dirty South (album)|The Dirty South]],'' and 2006's ''[[A Blessing and a Curse]].'' The title track of [[Decoration Day (album)|''Decoration Day'']] was revealed by Isbell in the 2014 ''[[Live from Lincoln Center]]'' concert to be a true story about his family members.<ref name=\"LiveLincCenter-2014\">{{cite web|url=http://video.pbs.org/video/2365214488/|title=Live From Lincoln Center - Jason Isbell: Moving Forward|work=[[PBS]]|date=11 April 2014|accessdate=6 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nFor most of his time as a band member, Isbell was married to [[Shonna Tucker]], who joined the band after Isbell as a bassist. The two were part of the band's documentary, ''The Secret to a Happy Ending.''<ref name=\"ref name=SecretHappyEnd-2011\">{{cite web|last=Weissman|first=Barr|title=The Secret to a Happy Ending|work=The Secret to a Happy Ending: A Documentary About the Drive-By Truckers|url=http://thesecrettoahappyending.com/|publisher=Full House Films / [[ATO Records]]|accessdate=7 May 2014|format=DVD release of the 2009 motion picture|year=2011}}</ref> The two later divorced.<ref name=\"BostonGlobe-2007\">{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/ae/music/articles/2007/07/15/hell_keep_on_trucking_but_solo/|title=He'll keep on trucking, but solo|last=Mitter|first=Siddhartha|date=15 July 2007|newspaper=[[Boston Globe]]|url-access=subscription |accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn April 5, 2007, Isbell announced that he was no longer a member of Drive-By Truckers. The following day, Patterson Hood confirmed the break on the band's official site. In his letter to the fans, Hood described the parting of ways as \"amicable\" and expressed the hope that fans would continue to support Drive-By Truckers as well as Jason's solo efforts.<ref name=Grantland-IsbellFired-2014>{{cite news|last1=Hyden|first1=Steven|title=Drive-By Truckers Carry On|url=http://grantland.com/features/drive-by-truckers-carry-on/|accessdate=9 August 2015|work=[[Grantland]]|date=4 March 2014}}</ref> Isbell had been with the Drive-By Truckers for six years.<ref name=CBS-SMTF-2015 />\n[[File:Jimbo Hart and Jason Isbell.jpg|thumb|Jimbo Hart (left) and Jason Isbell at Hardly Strictly Bluegrass in [[San Francisco]] on October 5, 2014.]]\n\nOn June 15, 2014, Isbell teamed with Hood and Mike Cooley for a benefit at the Shoals Theater in [[Florence, Alabama]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ells |first=Blake |url=http://countryfriedrock.org/hood-isbell-cooley-reunite-at-the-shoals-theater/#.Vzo0hk32bcs |title=Hood \u2013 Isbell \u2013 Cooley reunite at the Shoals Theater |publisher=Country Fried Rock |date=2014-06-19 |accessdate=2017-06-16}}</ref> The sold-out acoustic performance was the first time Isbell had performed with his former bandmates since they split in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesdaily.com/life/music/article_527f311e-dc68-11e3-b2e4-0017a43b2370.html |title=Benefit show with Truckers, Isbell sold out |website=Timesdaily.com |date=2014-05-15 |accessdate=2017-06-16}}</ref> In August 2015, Hood joined Isbell onstage and played a couple of Drive-By Truckers songs together in Hood's new adopted hometown of [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]].<ref name=\"Oregonian-IsbellHood-2015\">{{cite news|last1=Baker|first1=Jeff|title=Jason Isbell plays Drive-By Truckers songs with Patterson Hood at amazing Portland concert|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/music/index.ssf/2015/08/jason_isbell_plays_drive-by_tr.html|accessdate=9 August 2015|work=[[The Oregonian]]|date=9 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Solo work===\nJason Isbell released his first solo album, ''[[Sirens of the Ditch]]'', on July 10, 2007. In 2012, Isbell supported singer-songwriter [[Ryan Adams]] on his tour. Both played solo acoustic sets.\n\nOn June 11, 2013, Isbell released his fourth solo album, ''[[Southeastern (album)|Southeastern]].'' Produced by [[Dave Cobb]] and featuring accompanying vocals by [[Kim Richey]] and Isbell's wife, [[Amanda Shires]], ''Southeastern'' received overwhelmingly positive critical reviews, earning a score of 87<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/southeastern/jason-isbell|title=Southeastern by Jason Isbell|website=Metacritic|access-date=2016-05-10}}</ref> on [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"CMT-Ryman-2013\">{{cite web|last=Parton|first=Chris|title=Jason Isbell Leaves a Mark at Ryman|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1712559/jason-isbell-leaves-a-mark-at-ryman.jhtml|work=[[CMT (TV channel)|CMT]]|publisher=Country Music Television, Inc.|accessdate=30 March 2014|date=19 August 2013}}</ref> ''Southeastern'' led to Isbell's clean sweep of the [[Americana Music Honors & Awards|2014 Americana Music Awards]]. ''Southeastern'' won Album of the Year, Isbell was named Artist of the Year, and the song \"Cover Me Up\" was named Song of the Year.<ref name=\"NPR-Americana-2014\">{{cite web | title = Jason Isbell, Live at the 2014 Americana Music Awards |work= [[NPR]] | url = https://www.npr.org/event/music/364769222/jason-isbell-live-at-the-2014-americana-music-awards |author=Ann Powers|date=18 November 2014| accessdate = 19 November 2014}}</ref> [[NPR]] rock critic Ken Tucker listed ''Southeastern'' at No. 1 on his top ten albums of 2013. Isbell's record received praise by artists like [[Bruce Springsteen]] and [[John Prine]].<ref name=\"RollingStone-SMTF-2015\">{{cite news|last=Doyle|first=Patrick|title=Jason Isbell's New Morning|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/jason-isbells-new-morning-20150807|accessdate=9 August 2015|work=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]|date=7 August 2015}}</ref> Isbell's music video for the song \"Traveling Alone\" features the Jackson House, a historic home in [[Moulton, Alabama]].<ref name=TimesDaily-MusicVid-2013>{{cite news|last=Qualls|first=Meredith|title=Isbell's music video filmed in Moulton|url=http://www.timesdaily.com/life/music/article_d768c810-0b65-11e3-8caa-10604b9f7e7c.html|accessdate=29 March 2014|newspaper=TimesDaily|date=24 August 2013|location=Florence, AL}}</ref> In 2014, his song \"Cover Me Up\" was used as the weather for the ''[[Welcome to Night Vale]]'' episode \"Visitor\".\n\nIsbell's fifth solo record, ''[[Something More Than Free]],'' was released on July 17, 2015, on Southeastern Records. [[Dave Cobb]] produced, continuing the partnership created with Isbell on ''Southeastern.'' They recorded the album at [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]]'s Sound Emporium studio with a full band.<ref name=\"American-Songwriter-SMTF-2015\">{{cite news|last1=McKenna|first1=Brittney|title=Jason Isbell Announces New Album 'Something More Than Free'|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2015/04/jason-isbell-announces-new-album-something-free/|accessdate=17 April 2015|work=[[American Songwriter]]|date=16 April 2015}}</ref> During the summer of 2015, Isbell was on a North American tour to promote the album, with four consecutive sold-out nights at the [[Ryman Auditorium]] in Nashville at the end of October.<ref name=\"Radio-SMTF-2015\">{{cite web|url=http://radio.com/2015/04/16/jason-isbell-new-album-something-more-than-free-track-list-tour-dates/|title=Jason Isbell's New Album 'Something More Than Free' Coming in July|last=Wolff|first=Kurt|date=16 April 2015|website=Radio.com|accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"GratefulWeb-SummerDates-2015\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gratefulweb.com/articles/jason-isbell-summer-tour-dates-announced |title=Jason Isbell Summer Tour Dates Announced |work=Grateful Web|date=4 May 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref> In April 2016, Isbell appeared on the [[BBC]] live-music show ''[[Later... with Jools Holland|Later With Jools Holland]],'' singing \"The Life You Chose\", one of the tracks from ''Something More Than Free''.\n\nIsbell said that compared to ''Southeastern,'' ''Something More Than Free'' has a feeling of celebration,<ref name=\"RStone-SMTF-2015\">{{cite news|last1=Leahey|first1=Andrew|title=In the Studio With Jason Isbell Making 'Celebratory' New Album |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/in-the-studio-with-jason-isbell-making-celebratory-new-album-20150326|accessdate=1 June 2015|work=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]|date=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"FOLIOWkly-SMTF-2015\">{{cite news|last1=McGregor|first1=Nick|title=Jason Isbell's Workmanlike Genius|url=http://folioweekly.com/Jason-Isbells-Workmanlike-Genius,12502|accessdate=1 June 2015|work=FOLIO Weekly|date=6 May 2015}}</ref> which reflects his upcoming fatherhood and a forward-facing momentum.<ref name=\"DailyTimes-SMTF-2015\">{{cite news|last1=Wildsmith|first1=Steve|title=Freedom Songs: Singer-songwriter Jason Isbell builds a better album than 'Southeastern'|url=http://www.thedailytimes.com/entertainment/freedom-songs-singer-songwriter-jason-isbell-builds-a-better-album/article_e18ba738-5f7c-53da-a784-f1c800de2aa1.html|accessdate=1 June 2015|work=The Daily Times (Maryville, TN)|date=6 May 2015}}</ref> One track on the record, \"To a Band I Loved\", is a love-letter to the band [[Centro-Matic]], a now defunct band from [[Denton, Texas]], Isbell played with back in his Drive-By Truckers days.<ref name=\"RStone-SMTF-2015\" />\n\n''Something More Than Free'' debuted at number 1 on [[Billboard Magazine]]'s rock, folk and country record charts.<ref name=\"CBS-SMTF-2015\" /><ref name=\"Diffuser-SMTF-2015\">{{cite news|last=Kellmurray|first=Beth|title=Jason Isbell Celebrates the Chart Success of 'Something More Than Free'|url=http://diffuser.fm/jason-isbell-celebrates-the-chart-success-of-something-more-than-free/|accessdate=9 August 2015|work=[[Diffuser.fm]]|date=27 July 2015}}</ref> Although Isbell had had critical success in the [[Americana (music)|Americana]] genre, this was the first time he received such high ranking across genres.<ref name=\"Billboard-SMTF-2015\">{{cite news|last=Hight|first=Jewly |title=Country Star (and Expectant Dad) Jason Isbell 'Glad to Have My Baby on the Brain'|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/6649631/jason-isbell-interview-something-more-than-free-parenthood-amanda-shires|accessdate=9 August 2015|work=[[Billboard Magazine]]|date=5 August 2015}}</ref> The album was well received, winning two Grammy awards for Best Americana Album and Best American Roots Song (\"24 Frames\").<ref name=\"WSJ-SMTF-2015\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/something-more-than-free-by-jason-isbell-review-1438726208|title='Something More Than Free' by Jason Isbell Review|date=4 August 2015|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|url-access=subscription |last1=Mazor|first1=Barry|accessdate=13 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2016 Grammy Awards: Complete list of winners and nominees|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-grammys-2016-nominees-winners-list-story.html|accessdate=12 March 2016|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=15 February 2016}}</ref> On May 11, 2016, Isbell, a four-time winner, was nominated for three more [[Americana Music Honors & Awards]]: Album of the Year (''Something More Than Free''), Song of the Year (\"24 Frames\"), and Artist of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americanamusic.org/news/americana-honors-awards-nominees-announced |title=Americana Honors & Awards Nominees Announced |website=AmericanaMusic.org |date=2016-09-21 |accessdate=2017-06-16}}</ref> He won the first two, while [[Chris Stapleton]] won Artist of the Year.\n\n====Emergence of The 400 Unit====\nIsbell's band, [[Jason Isbell and The 400 Unit]], is primarily made up of musicians from the [[Muscle Shoals, Alabama]], area.<ref name=RollingStone-SXSW-2011>{{cite news|last=Helton|first=Eric|title=SXSW Interview: Jason Isbell|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/sxsw-interview-jason-isbell-20110318|accessdate=27 March 2014|newspaper=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=18 March 2011|format=video interview}}</ref> The lineup is:\n* Sadler Vaden, guitar, backup vocals - also of [[Drivin' N Cryin']]\n* Jimbo Hart, bass, backup vocals\n* Derry DeBorja, keyboard, accordion, backup vocals - formerly of [[Son Volt]]\n* Chad Gamble, drums, backup vocals - brother of [[Al Gamble]]\n* [[Amanda Shires]], fiddle, backup vocals\n\nThe band's name comes from the 400 Unit, a colloquial name for the psychiatric ward of Eliza Coffee Memorial Hospital in [[Florence, Alabama]]. It was originally called the 400 Unit because it was in a separate building from the main three-story hospital. After renovation in the 1980s, the ward was renamed as the Behavioral Health Center, also known as 1st North, and is located on the hospital's first floor.<ref name=FAME-Isbell-400Unit>{{cite web|title=Jason Isbell - Current Artists|url=http://www.fame2.com/current-artists/|work=FAME Music Group|accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nJason Isbell and The 400 Unit's [[Jason Isbell and The 400 Unit|eponymous album]] was released on February 17, 2009, on Lightning Rod Records. ''[[Jason Isbell and The 400 Unit]]'' was Isbell's second solo release and his first release with The 400 Unit. [[Matt Pence]] of [[Centro-Matic]] co-produced and engineered the record, as well as playing drums on the record.\n\nIsbell and the 400 Unit released their second album, ''[[Here We Rest]],'' on April 12, 2011, on Lightning Rod Records. The album was produced and recorded by the band. The song \"Alabama Pines\" was named Song of the Year at the 2012 [[Americana Music Award]]s.\n\nOn March 13, 2017, Isbell announced a new album with the 400 Unit, ''[[The Nashville Sound]]''. The album was released on June 16, 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/JasonIsbell/status/841317531491192832|title=Jason Isbell on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2017-03-13|language=en}}</ref> Isbell and the band won the [[Grammy Award for Best Americana Album]] and Isbell won [[Grammy Award for Best American Roots Song]] at the [[60th Annual Grammy Awards|60th ceremony]].\n\nIn October 2017, Isbell was announced to be the official artist-in-residence at the [[Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2017/10/16/jason-isbell-named-country-music-hall-fames-artist-in-residence/761975001/|title=Jason Isbell to perform at Country Music Hall of Fame as Artist-in-Residence|website=Tennessean.com}}</ref> He made a guest appearance on [[John Prine]]'s 2018 album ''[[The Tree of Forgiveness]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/allsongs/2018/02/08/584219320/john-prine-to-release-his-first-album-of-new-songs-in-13-years|title=John Prine To Release His First Album Of New Songs In 13 Years|website=Npr.org|accessdate=19 October 2018}}</ref> Isbell contributed the ballad \"Maybe It's Time\" to the soundtrack of the 2018 film [[A Star Is Born (2018 film)|A Star Is Born]], where it was performed by actor [[Bradley Cooper]]'s character, Jackson Maine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.spin.com/2018/08/a-star-is-born-soundtrack-release-date/|title=Soundtrack for A Star is Born, Starring Lady Gaga and Bradley Cooper, Announced}}</ref>\n\nOn February 11, 2020, Isbell announced a new album, ''Reunions''. It is scheduled to be released on May 15, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/jason-isbell-announces-new-album-reunions-share-new-song-be-afraid-listen/|title=Jason Isbell Announces New Album Reunions, Share New Song \"Be Afraid\": Listen|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|first=Sam|last=Sodomsky|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> ''Reunions'' sees Isbell once again working with producer [[Dave Cobb]] and features guest vocals by and Jay Buchanan of [[Rival Sons]] and [[David Crosby]]. The album announcement was made alongside the release of the first song of the album, \"Be Afraid\", which peaked at a career high number 5 on the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Billboard Adult Contemporary]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/jason-isbell-new-song-be-afraid-950171/|title=Jason Isbell Previews New Album 'Reunions' With Urgent Anthem 'Be Afraid'|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|first=Joseph|last=Hudak|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Musical influences==\nIsbell has stated on the importance of his northern Alabama roots: \"I definitely don't feel like I would be the musician that I am, or the type of songwriter, had I not come from that particular place,\" he says now. \"The soul music that came out of there, and a lot of the soul-influenced rock and roll and country music that came out of the studios in north Alabama in the 1960s and 1970s had a big influence on me.\"<ref name=Flagpole-Live-2012>{{cite web|last=Bailey|first=Rachel|title=Jason Isbell: That New Southern Style|url=http://flagpole.com/music/music-features/2012/11/28/jason-isbell|work=[[Flagpole Magazine]]|accessdate=29 March 2014|date=28 November 2012}}</ref> Isbell said that working at FAME Studios was everything to him, that it was a gateway towards the music that he wanted to play.<ref name=CBS-SMTF-2015 /> In addition to citing [[Neil Young]] as a big influence, Isbell is a fan of singer-songwriter [[Ben Howard]] and guitarist [[Blake Mills]].<ref name=HuffPo-SMTF-2015 />\n\n==Personal life==\nIsbell married singer-songwriter and [[violinist]] [[Amanda Shires]], with whom he had worked on and off for a decade, in February 2013, two days after they finished ''Southeastern.''<ref name=LATimes-2013 /><ref name=LubbockAvJourn-2012>{{cite web|last=Kerns|first=William|title=Happily engaged Shires makes return appearance in hometown |url=http://lubbockonline.com/entertainment/2012-07-25/happily-engaged-shires-makes-return-appearance-hometown#.UsTbk2RDvt3|work=[[Lubbock Avalanche-Journal]]|accessdate=1 January 2014|date=25 July 2012}}</ref> Musician [[Todd Snider]] officiated their wedding.<ref name=WTF-Maron-2014 /> The couple had a baby girl, Mercy Rose,<ref>{{cite web|title = Amanda Shires Isbell on Twitter|url = https://twitter.com/amandashires/status/640666061235486720|website = Twitter|accessdate = 2015-11-17}}</ref> on September 1, 2015.<ref name=DemChronicle-TourPreview-2015>{{cite news|last1=Spevak|first1=Jeff|title=Jason Isbell: The craft of sadness at Water Street|url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/lifestyle/columnist/spevak/2015/05/19/jason-isbell-craft-sadness-water-street/27567259/|accessdate=1 June 2015|work=[[Democrat & Chronicle]]|date=19 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=Instagram-Baby-2015>{{cite web|last1=Isbell|first1=Jason|title=jasonisbell on Istagram: \"Today\"|url=https://instagram.com/p/7GRGleFDyh/|website=[[Instagram]]|accessdate=1 September 2015|date=1 September 2015}}</ref> Isbell was previously married to [[Shonna Tucker]], a fellow musician from the [[Muscle Shoals, Alabama]] community and a former bass player from [[Drive-By Truckers]]. Isbell and Tucker got married in 2002.<ref name=\"NYT-Mag-2013\" />\n\nIn February 2012, Amanda Shires, Isbell's manager Traci Thomas and [[Ryan Adams]] initiated an [[intervention (counseling)|intervention]], leading to Isbell entering a rehabilitation treatment program at Cumberland Heights in Nashville.<ref name=\"NYT-Mag-2013\" /> Isbell has discussed getting [[sobriety|sober]] extensively, saying he drank [[Jack Daniel's]] and did [[cocaine]] during his time with [[Drive-By Truckers]] in his late 20s\u2014a time he does not remember very clearly.<ref name=\"FreshAir-NPR-2013\">{{cite web|last=Gross|first=Terry|title=Jason Isbell Locates His Musical Compass On 'Southeastern'|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/07/17/202369759/jason-isbell-locates-his-musical-compass-on-southeastern|work=[[Fresh Air]]|publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=30 March 2014|date=17 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"HuffPo-Hangout-2013\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/michael-bialas/hangout-and-about-part-1_b_3205051.html|title=Hangout and About, Part 1: Jason Isbell is Solo, But Not Alone|last=Bialas|first=Michael|date=3 May 2013|newspaper=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=30 March 2014}}</ref> ''Southeastern'', Isbell's 2013 solo album, is reflective of his newfound sober lifestyle.<ref name=\"NPR-SE-sobriety-2013\">{{cite web|last=Block|first=Melissa|title=Jason Isbell: A 'Southeastern' Songwriter's Path To Sobriety|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/06/10/190372187/jason-isbell-a-southeastern-songwriters-path-to-sobriety|work=[[All Things Considered]]|publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=7 May 2014|format=Audio interview|date=10 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nIsbell has a tattoo on the inside of his left arm with a quotation from the lyrics of the [[Bob Dylan]] song \"[[Boots of Spanish Leather]]\".<ref name=\"LATimes-2013\">{{cite news|last=Lacher|first=Irene|title=The Sunday Conversation: A sobering change for singer Jason Isbell|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/07/entertainment/la-et-jason-isbell-conversation|accessdate=27 March 2014|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=7 September 2013}}</ref> He said that the quote reminds him about the idea of salvaging things, that for him it evokes the idea of loss as well as learning and growing from the experience.<ref name=\"CBS-SMTF-2015\" /> During the 2015 [[Newport Folk Festival]], Isbell cited Dylan as a huge influence on his writing.<ref name=\"Relix-DylansGuitar-2015\">{{cite news|title=Watch: Jason Isbell Plays Bob Dylan's Guitar from the 1965 Newport Folk Festival|url=https://www.relix.com/blogs/detail/watch_jason_isbell_plays_bob_dylans_guitar_from_the_1965_newport_folk_festival|accessdate=9 August 2015|work=[[Relix]]|date=6 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIsbell has lived in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], since 2011.<ref name=\"AmSongwriter-2013\" /><ref name=\"SeriousEats-2012\">{{cite web|last=Portman|first=Jed|title=Down South: Southern Rock Star Jason Isbell on Cracker Barrel, Cornbread Poetry, and More|url=http://www.seriouseats.com/2012/12/jason-isbell-southern-rock-music-food.html|work=[[Serious Eats]]|accessdate=30 March 2014|date=7 December 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"CMT-Americana-2012\">{{cite news|last=Shelburne|first=Craig|title=Jason Isbell Finds Americana in \"Alabama Pines\"|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1690462/jason-isbell-finds-americana-in-alabama-pines.jhtml|accessdate=30 March 2014|newspaper=[[CMT (TV channel)|CMT]]|date=25 July 2012}}</ref> He is an [[Atlanta Braves]] fan and a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]].<ref name=\"AJC-Braves-2011\">{{cite news|last=O'Brien|first=David|title=For Jason Isbell, Braves fandom runs in family|url=http://blogs.ajc.com/atlanta-braves-blog/2011/12/15/for-jason-isbell-braves-fandom-runs-in-family/|accessdate=30 March 2014|newspaper=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=15 December 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105223850/http://blogs.ajc.com/atlanta-braves-blog/2011/12/15/for-jason-isbell-braves-fandom-runs-in-family/|archivedate=5 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/ex-drive-by-trucker-jason-isbell-interview-i-have-a-hard-time-accepting-taylor-swift-as-a-sexy-adult-10395765.html|title=Jason Isbell : 'I have a hard time accepting Taylor Swift as a sexy adult'|date=2015-07-17|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-09-06}}</ref> In November 2017, Isbell was asked on Twitter \"Why do we have to inject politics in every aspect of our life can't we just enjoy the music and the football games?\" He responded \"Until you are the one being treated unfairly, that's easy to say.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/03/arts/music/cma-awards-politics.html|title=Country Music Association Tells Journalists Not to Talk About Guns, Politics or Las Vegas|last=Victor|first=Daniel|date=2017-11-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-11-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Martin D-18 Jason Isbell Signature Edition Guitar==\nIsbell worked closely with the Custom Shop at Martin Guitar to design his signature D-18. Similar to Martin\u2019s Authentic series, Jason\u2019s Custom is constructed using hide glue, which unlike newer synthetic reproductions, dissolves into the grain of the wood and creates more resonance throughout the instrument. Isbell added a personal touch by adding an inlay of one of his tattoos at the twelfth fret. He also chose a thin finish and left off the pickguard \u2013 both design details that have one common goal \u2013 to make it loud. \u201cGrowing up with my granddad and his brothers and their Martins, whoever had the loudest guitar always had the best,\u201d Isbell says. \u201cSo I wanted to make the loudest D-18 we could make.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.martinguitar.com/about/news/martin-guitar-to-debut-d-18-jason-isbell-signature-edition-at-summer-namm-2017/|title=Martin Guitar to Debut D-18 Jason Isbell Signature Edition at Summer NAMM 2017|website=martinguitar.com}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\nJason Isbell is referenced in the song \"Mr. Tillman\" by [[Father John Misty]] on his 2018 album ''[[God's Favorite Customer]]''.\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Album details\n! colspan=\"8\"| Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:9em;\"| Sales\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br /><ref>{{cite magazine|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Jason Isbell|chart=Billboard 200}} |title=Jason Isbell Album Chart History: Billboard 200 |magazine=Billboard.com }}</ref><ref name=\"BB200\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jason-isbell-and-the-400-unit/chart-history/billboard-200 |title=Jason Isbell & the 400 Unit Chart History: Billboard 200 |work=Billboard |accessdate=October 30, 2018}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Top Heatseekers|US Heat]]<br /><ref>{{cite magazine|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Jason Isbell|chart=Heatseekers Albums}} |title=Jason Isbell Album Chart History: Heatseekers Albums |magazine=Billboard.com }}</ref><ref name=\"billboard biz\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/search/charts?f[0]=ts_chart_artistname%3Ajason%20isbell&f[1]=ss_bb_type%3Achart_item&type=2&artist=jason%20isbell|title=Billboard.biz |magazine=Billboard.com }} Search under Charts for Jason Isbell</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Independent Albums|US Indie]]<br /><ref name=\"billboard biz\" /><ref name=\"indie\">{{cite magazine|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Jason Isbell|chart=Independent Albums}} |title=Jason Isbell Chart History: Independent Albums |magazine=Billboard.com }}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Top Country Albums|US Country]]<br /><ref>{{cite magazine|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Jason Isbell|chart=Country Albums}} |title=Jason Isbell Album Chart History: Top Country Albums |magazine=Billboard.com }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/7757575/jason-isbell-the-400-unit/chart?f=320 |title= & the 400 Unit Album Chart History: Top Country Albums  |magazine=Billboard.com }}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Folk Albums|US Folk]]<br /><ref>{{cite magazine|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Jason Isbell|chart=Folk Albums}} |title=Jason Isbell Album Chart History: Folk Albums |magazine=Billboard.com }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/7757575/jason-isbell-the-400-unit/chart?f=1071 |title= & the 400 Unit Album Chart History: Americana/Folk Albums  |magazine=Billboard.com }}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Top Rock Albums|US Rock]]<br /><ref name=\"billboard biz\" /><ref>{{cite magazine|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Jason Isbell|chart=Rock Albums}} |title=Jason Isbell Album Chart History: Top Rock Albums |magazine=Billboard.com }}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Jason+Isbell|title=australian-charts.com \u2013 Discography Jason Isbell|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=June 24, 2017}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/20132/jason-isbell/ |title=Jason Isbell |work=The Official UK Charts Company }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Sirens of the Ditch]]''\n| \n* Release date: July 10, 2007\n* Label: [[New West Records]]\n| \u2014\n| 10\n| 33\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Jason Isbell and The 400 Unit]]''\n| \n* Release date: February 17, 2009\n* Label: Lightning Rod Records\n| 131\n| 3\n| 17\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Here We Rest]]''\n| \n* Release date: April 12, 2011\n* Label: Lightning Rod Records\n| 79\n| 